definition.value: A fenchone that has (1R,4S)-stereochemistry. It is a constituent of the essential oils obtained from fennel.

Any terpenoid derived from a triterpene. The term includes compounds in which the C30 skeleton of the parent triterpene has been rearranged or modified by the removal of one or more skeletal atoms (generally methyl groups).
A naphthyridine in which the nitrogens are at positions 1 and 4.
An azaarene that is the 1,2-diaza analogue of naphthalene. The parent of the class of cinnolines.
A mancude organic heterobicyclic parent that is naphthalene in which the carbon atoms at positions 1 and 3 have been replaced by nitrogen atoms.
A mancude organic heterobicyclic parent that is a heterocyclic organic compound comprising fused benzene and imidazole rings.
Any one of eight organic heterobicyclic compounds that have a naphthalene skeleton in which two of the carbons are replaced by nitrogens. A 'closed' class.
A naphthyridine in which the nitrogens are situated at positions 1 and 8.
A cholesterol ester obtained by the formal condensation of cholesterol with palmitic acid.
A methylbenzoic acid that is benzoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 2.
A methylbenzoic acid in which the methyl substituent is located at position 4.
Any oligoglycosylceramide where the oligoglycoside component is a nonasaccharide.
An oligoglycosylceramide consisting of a glycooctaosyl moiety attached to the ceramide oxygen with an unspecified N-acyl substituent attached to the ceramide nitrogen.
The conjugate base of glyoxylic acid.
A member of the class of glyoxylates, that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of phenylglyoxylic acid.
A hydroxybenzoate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 6-methylsalicylic acid.
A 2-hydroxy carboxylate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)lactic acid.
